commit_message:
Avoid comparision between "None" type and "int" type.

In py34, if NoneType object is compared to int value
it raises exception.
In unit test following type of error is occured.
"TypeError: unorderable types: NoneType() >= int()".

Change-Id: Ibc7329824324edbe30976d460d389299824574ce
Partially-Implements: blueprint mistral-py3

commit_message:
Add 410 error code handling to REST client

- Add Gone exception which will raised if REST client hits
error code 410.
- Add unit tests for this exception.

Change-Id: I543fa80875d6de00845d5dc26bc07da2c1a7cd09

commit_message:
Fixed some unit test issue.

1) 'output' property has been added to WF_EXECS.
2) In py34,'message' attrubute has been removed
   from exception class. So 'args[0]' has been
   used instead of 'message'.

Partially-Implements: blueprint mistral-py3

Change-Id: I626de3d9305f4f8d52bbeaf2b1094c9e96563cae

How come this callback feature not generally available to all types of actions?'}, {'account_id': 5558, 'date': '2015-11-16 23:50:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 7700, 'date': '2015-11-17 08:29:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Hi, Winson, this callback URL is allowed only for async actions, that's why I added it to action_context. The main goal here - to provide callback URL for async actions without almost any knowledge about Mistral task-executions or action-executions. It is needed only for async actions since sync actions doesn't need it because they immediately send the result back to engine. What am I missing?"}, {'account_id': 6732, 'date': '2015-11-17 14:07:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 5558, 'date': '2015-11-17 17:21:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Nikolay, then why not make the callback URL available an abstract async action (i.e. base.AsyncAction) and have HTTP action inherit from that instead of setting this up only for the HTTP action in the headers?'}, {'account_id': 7700, 'date': '2015-11-17 19:11:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Callback URL in this patch is available for all async actions, not only std.mistral_http. See this at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/245772/1/mistral/services/action_manager.py

Action context is available for all async actions, just specify is_sync method to return False and constructor of this async action should contain action_context argument. See at https://github.com/openstack/mistral/blob/master/mistral/actions/std_actions.py#L225

That is the contract of how to write async actions in Mistral.'}, {'account_id': 5558, 'date': '2015-11-17 20:41:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Adding callback url to action context

 * Callback URL is now provided by std.mistral_http
 action to easy understand where the result should be sent

Closes-Bug: #1500833

Change-Id: I347edc5848bde4262a2d57f1787db5f16e218f0a

commit_message:
Remove iso8601 dependency

Mistral does not import and use this module directly, no need to list
it in the requirements and no need to set debug level for this module.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I42d5661dce0d23777fc5801c20a3a7c86756007d
(cherry picked from commit 91f35ae9fb8d4efc042baa3028f7c7369219d280)

This change introduced another issue in cinder.

If multiple volumes are attached to an instance and we try to swap a volume "in-use" with another volume "available", swap-volume fails with error message "NotImplementedError: Swap only supports host devices" but the volume status has been swapped by cinder api.

It looks worse as the attached volume status is set to "available" and the volume which is set to "in-use" is not attached to the instance.
Where as volume status remains unchanged in case of swap-volume failure before this patch is merged which looks reasonable.

Steps to reproduce: https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1489744/comments/6'}]

Previously the swap_volume was changed in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/101932 and

attach and detach logic to Cinder, however those changes only fix

commit_message:
Fix swap_volume for case without migration

Fix swap_volume so that even when a volume-migration does not
occur, the volumes don't get stuck in "attaching" and "detaching".
Previously the swap_volume was changed in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/101932 and
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/101933 to move the final
attach and detach logic to Cinder, however those changes only fix
the migration path.  This change calls Cinder's "attach" and "detach"
for the non-migration path to update the volumes' states.

Change-Id: I242c2c7c4a7197bbce04d0b3d75688f989ea1fd5
Closes-Bug: #1489744

How exactly volume_types (plural) in client and API match with volume_type_id (singular) in DB? Looking at the code it seems we're saving comma-separated ids in the DB, which seems like a bad way to describe n-n relationshipâ¦

Anyway if we're having n-n relationship in create API we shouldn't have n-1 relationship in get API. We should return a list there.

And another thing - if we're allowing list in create API, we should use list parameters in the client, not explicit comma-separated values.

Am I misunderstanding something? It seems we're abusing correct ways to represent n-n relationships here."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-11-16 14:51:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Agree that the comma separated id's is not good.  I do have plan to change that to use a list, however, we need to remove the volume_type_id from consistencygroups as part of that change.  Is the removal of a column a problem for rolling upgrades?"}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-11-16 15:11:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@xing-yang: It is. I'm writing a spec right now that will describe a way to do that. I think I'll have it ready for reviews today or tomorrow.

At least for a release we would need to live with old and new way to describe cg<->volume_type relationship.

In case of this commit - I would love to make that info consumable for Horizon. Even without changing the internals we can start to expose volume_type_id as a list in JSON response:

    {
        "volume_types": ["uuid1", "uuid2"],
    }

As we need to maintain API compatibility I believe we should start with a correct way to represent list instead of comma-separated-values.

Does it make sense?'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-11-16 16:04:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Michal,

I agree with your suggestion.  We don't want Horizon to make additional change when we change APIs."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-11-16 16:07:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Can you make changes suggested by Michal?  Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 16917, 'date': '2015-11-16 16:57:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
CG API should return volume type IDs

The create method of consistency group API requires a list of
volume type ids; volumes belonging to only these types can be added
to the consistency group. The get method of the consistency group API
does not, however, return the volume type id information.

Horizon needs this value for its "Add volumes to consistency group"
panel so that it can filter the "available volumes" list to only
show volumes that match the volume type associated with the consistency
group.

This was fixed by propagating the volume type id information in
the api layer (this information is stored in the db, it just wasn't
being propagated).

APIImpact
The get method of the consistency group API now returns the volume
type ids information.

DocImpact
The screenshots in the admin guide (see
http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/blockstorage-consistency-groups.html)
should be updated to show this new field.

Change-Id: Icc3206c67227af38a7bf89ea0145942f750b506b
Closes-Bug: #1489957

Sorry, but I think this is very corner case as integrated test.
And unit tests of Nova itself already contain this kind of test. So I think we don't need to spend test operating time for this on all OpenStack projects. (If the test is merged into Tempest, all projects' gate tests run the test in most cases)"}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-11-25 08:12:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ken'ichi, I am 100% sure that Nova also has unittest for updating instance name with ASCII symbols, however, we have such a check in Tempest. Also unittest doesn't create a real instance and doesn't update its name like it is done in this test. IMHO, we shouldn't exclude this check only because Nova contains unittest that checks it :)"}, {'account_id': 13454, 'date': '2015-11-25 17:20:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 7350, 'date': '2015-11-25 17:27:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

I agree that this test doesn't bring a lot, maybe it's even a duplicate from what is already tested in Nova. But the test is here and works. Now, this change doesn't add a new test but merely update an existing test so that non-ascii characters are tested.

Again, the main point here is that this change doesn't add a single API call to Nova."}, {'account_id': 7428, 'date': '2015-11-25 17:46:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Test v2 tokens being deleted by v3

This test illustrates that v2 tokens deleted by v3 do not work on v2.

Change-Id: Ia87fc785afe624fde0ad191cc6f031eb7605096e
Related-Bug: 1464377
(cherry picked from commit 0941a5e46391bfeecac1247d12604fcb78047cb7)

commit_message:
Fix T110 violations for image_client

image_client contained T110 violations, and we need to fix them
before migrating the client to tempest-lib for consistent interfaces.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I376efbc703762473ab69bfe424064bf32c4e78a5

Added a heat template to build Faafo

The added template builds Faafo as an all-in-one install.

commit_message:
Added an autoscaling heat template

The template scales the workers both up and down,
dependent on the load across all of the workers. The
orchestration text has been modified to describe
how it all hangs together.

Change-Id: I5959a734ecb21476ab6359cacf49317d370cd0a5

commit_message:
Add summaries for guides on docs.openstack.org

Adds a summary line for each guide on docs.openstack.org
in order to help users find the appropriate book for
their needs.

Adds ".docs-link-sections p" to combined.css to style
the summary lines.

Changes applied to Juno, Kilo, Liberty, and Mitaka.

Change-Id: Ibcbc3d18981a58184646f55b93e77032e4f6c1c0

commit_message:
Scenarios: cleanup class scope variable usage

This removes the class variables for 'server', 'volume' and 'image'
so we don't rely on tight coupling between method calls.

Related-Bug: #1482299
Change-Id: I03aa4e4e4dab9ad9e41175f493fc4535b8dd0f2c

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-25 19:06:08.000000000', 'message': 'Include params in multipart message part content-type

The content-type header inserted into a multipart message part
is missing any params such as charset because its value is being
fetched via the swob.Response content_type property, which conforms
to webob spec and strips off all params.

This was noticed in work on feature/crypto branch because the crypto
meta param was being stripped off content-type in multipart messages,
preventing the content-type being decrypted. But in general there is
no suggestion in the multipart message spec [1] that params should
not be included. In fact examples in [1] show the charset param
included in the content-type value.

To ensure that the multipart message part content-type includes the
original content-type params, fetch it directly from the response
headers.

[1] http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc1341/7_2_Multipart.html

Change-Id: Iff7274aa631a92cd7332212ed8b4378c27da4a1f
'}]
commit_message:
Include params in multipart message part content-type

The content-type header inserted into a multipart message part
is missing any params such as charset because its value is being
fetched via the swob.Response content_type property, which conforms
to webob spec and strips off all params.

This was noticed in work on feature/crypto branch because the crypto
meta param was being stripped off content-type in multipart messages,
preventing the content-type being decrypted. But in general there is
no suggestion in the multipart message spec [1] that params should
not be included. In fact examples in [1] show the charset param
included in the content-type value.

To ensure that the multipart message part content-type includes the
original content-type params, fetch it directly from the response
headers.

[1] http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc1341/7_2_Multipart.html

Change-Id: Iff7274aa631a92cd7332212ed8b4378c27da4a1f

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute security_group_default_rule

Compute security_group_default_rule has been migrated to
tempest-lib- I8b652aeb82d2a7335212ef7cc021a969ad297c6a

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commit makes Tempest to use compute security_group_default_rule
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I6be919a2845a08426758d19890919e6d97d2161d

commit_message:
Add project_id to extension URL

os-extensions need project_id in order to find resource.
The doc need to tell user it's needed.

Also, add os-server-external-events as sample to resource
alias instead of name like ServerExternalEvents.

(df) removed unused samples
(df) moved samples to extension-info folder

Change-Id: Ia46fed559e94a55c20281e5ebc1d4ef08118566c
Partial-Bug: 1515222

commit_message:
return all endpoints if service type is empty

Currently we only return endpoints related to a specific service
type from service catalog, this patch enables return all endpoints
if service type is empty.

Change-Id: I8f61941664f6dea9521346dac53cc47bd1e09542
Related-Bug: #1451336

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-10-14 14:54:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Dmitry said that the goal was to split up manager.py because the file was too big and he wanted to split up the class into subclasses.

wrt futurist, which deals with periodic tasks, my first (maybe dumb) question was why not split the periodic-task-like methods into a subclass and leave the rest in manager.py.

Wrt the actual splitting in this patch, the idea seems fine, although I have some thoughts. I don't like 'api'; there are too many 'apis' floating around. How about 'operation' ('op'?) or 'command' ('cmd')? (I prefer 'operation' so folks don't confuse 'command' with API/commands that they think they can invoke but maybe that is a plus for using 'command').

Whatever XYZ we use, I'd prefer the breakdown like:
- base_XYZ.py with class ConductorXYZ
- node_XYZ.py
- port_XYZ.py

commit_message:
Move common code from ironic.conductor.manager to ironic.conductor.utils

This is the first patch in a chain of refactoring patches in preparation
for moving to Futurist library. See blueprint futurist for details.

Moving *_error_handler from manager.py to utils.py as they're used
in many places, including outside of conductor. Also moving
set_node_cleaning_step. This should simplify defining public API
for 3rdparty drivers later on.

Change-Id: I2de8f45a813f1a54f97d1ef763288c81cb37e9e8

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute quotas_client

Compute quotas_client has been migrated to
tempest-lib- Ib0fcb82ce09ea68d9899836264e8037ac977347b

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commit makes Tempest to use compute quotas_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: Idbe0014ee44a74af02753848d244b8360bb5f9fc

commit_message:
reduce keyboard interactive when run deployer

We should specify -y option when install packages, to reduce unnecessary
user required interactive.

Also this patch replaces tab characters with spaces.

Change-Id: I9b7f47d2c32997d510473f492d747b767ab1f628

commit_message:
Removes discover from test-reqs

The discover package is part of Python 2.7, so we don't need
to explicitely require it. It's by the way annoying for
distribution package maintainers, as the file has to be
patched.

Keystone team has decided to drop python 2.6 support[1],
so, it's safe to remove it from test-requirements.txt.

[1] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/keystone/2015/keystone.2015-11-24-17.59.html

Change-Id: I31acab336691d2d49275dd7ae654c8b7e9b76fcc
Co-Authored-By: Thomas Goirand <thomas@goirand.fr>

commit_message:
Updates keystone region constraints for endpoint

OS::Keystone::Endpoint region property is updated to
validate with keystone.region

implements blueprint: heat-keystone-region-resource

Change-Id: I4bc75c428d10376711d3852d240e4da6e46f36cc

commit_message:
Parameter checking for cluster-policy-update

This adds parameter checking for cluster-policy-update. The checks are
actually reusing the same logic as that for cluster-policy-attach.

Change-Id: Id8f8886b25ceb2bb138cf2a2b014db72ae6a3c92

commit_message:
Parameter checking for cluster-policy-detach

This adds checking if a policy is actually specified when the REST API
cluster-policy-detach is invoked.

Change-Id: Ifa8d41d92a3024d4662cf66af4ac9b15c4268d68
Closes-Bug: #1465518

My concern with this patch is that prior to this, I am not sure we made any distinction between reraising exceptions or not, if something is done in a worker thread. I don't think the method itself should know if it is in a worker thread in the background. What if something changes in the future and it is eg reused in a foreground thread?

What is the problem with re-raising an exception?"}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2015-11-09 15:55:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm pretty sure we usually avoid to raising exceptions in the background thread. The problem is that eventlet is going to show an ugly traceback, probably nothing important."}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2015-11-10 01:48:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

yes, we can't catch the exception raised by backgroud thread, and I'm not sure why we need to spawn a background worker to set console mode, this way, we don't know whether it succeed or not."}, {'account_id': 19258, 'date': '2015-11-26 03:01:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

it is a good patch! there's no way to catch the reraise exception for a thread worker that work in the backgroud. is the linux limit it?"}]

commit_message:
Don't reraise the exception in _set_console_mode

As _set_console_mode runs in a thread worker in the backgroud,
there's no way to catch the reraise exception, so change to log
an error message to handle this more gracefully.

Closes-Bug: #1513858
Change-Id: I0df54e6600a47b627d1442e92f80f0ff8654e616

commit_message:
Silence most of the deprecation spam

Running keystoneclient unittest is really painful, because it's
impossible to see what failed in all of the deprecation output.

Make most of it go away. There is still a chunk that is being elusive.

Change-Id: I006859b016274fc1adf69653ff75b3071d2c9446

commit_message:
fix the swift-hash-path parameter mismatch

In Swift-finalize-installation swift hash path prefix and suffix values are
mistakenly written in swapped order.

Change-Id: If9d290814116b7d0d24fa49ada8cea7327ec49fa
Closes-Bug: #1518651

commit_message:
Tarball-constraints should only run on liberty+

'{name}-tarball-constraints should never run on releases prior to
liberty.  Add a broad regex rule to catch this.

Change-Id: Ieee4e1392ffe919eab90b80a702fcca77d333577
Closes-Bug: 1519750

commit_message:
Bring back Python 2.6 compat (don"t use dict comprehension)

We have a couple of places where we use dict comprehension. Dict
comprehension are just syntaxic sugar and can be replaced with
dict((k,v) for k,v in iterable) for Python 2.6 compat

I know Tempest doesn"t support Python 2.6 anymore and I agree it's
the good decision. But I am not a fan of "dropping support for the
sake of it", without compeling reason (like using a new module).

I am in charge of a 3rd party CI and my employer wants to have
Centos 6 support for OpenStack Juno. We use Tempest as our non-reg
test suite. Tempest is branchless.

This patch brings back Python 2.6 compatibility.

Change-Id: I23aeafcc9e68d09342a773d2e202f01884080fa3

commit_message:
Catch InvalidImageStatusTransition error

Now, when delete image to unallowed status, it will raise a 500
error. So we should catch that error to avoid it.

Change-Id: I47f777a81a6069793dfa4d52eace79edb266669d
Closes-bug: #1505474
(cherry picked from commit 1f8511d8b09c5199a57588e8312a46441fbcd7a6)

commit_message:
Ensure ephemeral user's user_id is url-safe

As a principle, an attribute ``user_id`` should always be url safe and
we should make sure this is the case especially for the federated
authentication workflow as user name and id can be provided directly
from the user (either hardcoded in the mapping rule or passed as a
parameter from the assertion).

Change-Id: I7256a5e4d31d3c2e55fe956fb0170452bb241078
Closes-Bug: #1487115
(cherry picked from commit 02f8576ddf2fca67849171aa7a1b41ebcfa90ded)

commit_message:
Show that unscoped tokens are revoked when deleting role assignments

Unscoped tokens should, in fact, NOT be revoked when deleting role
assignments, but this test demonstrates the opposite behavior to be the
case.

Change-Id: Ie4c844b4c2c8dae5d9f6b01404fd153b8155870d
Partial-Bug: 1488208
(cherry picked from commit 5ced3c77430d9a0bd871d5387c9aadb9df1c0060)

commit_message:
Check shellinabox started successfully or not

Shellinabox daemon always return 0 and leave pid file even if it
started failed, so this patch checks whether the process is running.

Change-Id: I1ac32d4b0d0248bdffdce7a7cf88102f58f1c0da
Closes-Bug: #1516897

commit_message:
Set start/stop pacemaker resource timeouts for updates

This matches change I6fc18f1ad876c5a25723710a3b20d8ec9519dcba, but we
need it to set it before attempting the cluster stop - yum update -
cluster start cycle, to make sure this cycle doesn't hit the low timeout
limits.

This can be removed once updates from deployments made prior to
I6fc18f1ad876c5a25723710a3b20d8ec9519dcba are no longer supported.

Change-Id: I587136d8d045d213875c657ea5a405074f80c8ad
(cherry picked from commit 5c2d5e335b84485808094173e006e520ccd522db)

commit_message:
Add missing constraints in yum_update.sh

Some missing pacemaker constraints were added in the following commits:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/219770/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/219665/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/218931/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/218930/

Overclouds that were deployed prior to these constraints being added to
tripleo-heat-templates still have the constraints missing. During an
update, stopping and starting the cluster can fail without these
constraints in place.  As a workaround, conditionally add these
contraints in yum_update.sh so that we're sure they're always present
before updating.

Change-Id: Id46c85dbbe5e85d362279661091b17ce1b697fe0
(cherry picked from commit bfb698e82becf7f53c670618365311029b4f73b8)

commit_message:
Refactor IRMCVirtualMediaAgentDeploy by applying new BootInterface

This patch refactors IRMCVirtualMediaAgentDeploy by applying new
BootInterface. Consequently IRMCVirtualMediaAgentDeploy is divided
into IRMCVirtualMediaBoot and IRMCVirtualMediaAgentDeploy.

Implements: blueprint irmc-driver-uses-boot-interface

Change-Id: I7cae6588dfeffec3c5667ecabdb164ca72d63f22

commit_message:
Removes discover from test-reqs

The discover package is part of Python 2.7, so we don't need
to explicitely require it. It's by the way annoying for
distribution package maintainers, as the file has to be
patched.

Keystone team has decided to drop python 2.6 support[1],
so, it's safe to remove it from test-requirements.txt.

[1] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/keystone/2015/keystone.2015-11-24-17.59.html

Related-Bug: #1519449
Co-Authored-By: Thomas Goirand <thomas@goirand.fr>
Change-Id: I5bb258a4b305c0084be50bc22fe7a0e6a4f65aad

commit_message:
Add "httpchk /versions" for glance-api haproxy.

With the default httpchk, glance-api always show warning in the logs
"WARNING glance.api.middleware.version_negotiation [..] Unknown version.
Returning version choices", with the /versions added, there is no
warning in the log.

Change-Id: I086cb23c30b9e3ddc5eac68cba42d03ed907138c
(cherry picked from commit 2a2da2f5aa271eebb06016060c62eee4618a0228)

commit_message:
Remove useless ResourceManager.register_model()

All the d6cage API service objects are contained in
ElementHandler and CollectionHandler, so that isn't
necessary to register model, remove the related logic
and method.

Change-Id: I7cb0bf05085864c77c731869946bcee551228ae1

commit_message:
Remove execute table from policy table list

Now when we create a reactive policy, like:
'execute[nova:servers.pause(x)] :- nova:servers(id=x, status="ACTIVE")',
the tables 'nova:servers.pause' and 'nova:servers' will present in the
output of 'congress policy table list', the user might want to list table
rows by the table 'nova:servers.pause', that shouldn't be supported by
Congress, 'nova:servers.pause' is just a service API or user-defined
function, not a regular table, so filter this type table out from
policy.tablenames(), avoid this operation.

Change-Id: I9846d67dbbb8f808ee5a78d0c3317fd04ac68896
Closes-Bug: #1454844

commit_message:
Remove flake8 test from gate-check-commit

The flake8 test has been moved to tox and its own gate check, so it
may be removed from the gate-check-commit script.

Change-Id: I952d73b994c681db3cd44cb8df65727b1b2a23a9
(cherry picked from commit 7e6e4d81addbbf636a2ae0d3f2b106bc8498dec9)

commit_message:
Fix description field in schema for Nova

Currently, description is always None when showing schema of datasource
or schema of particular table of datasource.

This commit only fixes for nova datasource.

Change-Id: I927b4d252fe4be085d5c7a3cdc95e8a68487b9d8
Partial-Bug:#1498398

commit_message:
initialize ceilometerclient when we use it

There is a chance that ceilometerclient cannot be initialized if
keystone is not available, putting the initialization in __init__
will fail to load threshold extension for such case.

This patch moves the initialization out from __init__ to a dedicate
property method.

Change-Id: I24895126c3efe9920390401e4d10a2ce6b1f1376
Closes-Bug: #1518447

[{'created': '2015-11-25 12:55:38.000000000', 'message': "Use sudo for role testing

There are 2 ways to realize the privilege escalation needed for the gate jobs.

1) Editing the playbooks (and hope to not forget to write the sudo/become lines for every role)

2) Editing the inventory and set the variable there.

I'm taking the second approach with the minimum set of variables (become_method is sudo by default and become_user is root by default).

commit_message:
Use sudo for role testing

There are 2 ways to realize the privilege escalation
needed for the gate jobs.

1) Editing the playbooks (and hope to not forget to
write the sudo/become lines for every role)
2) Editing the inventory and set the variable there.

I'm taking the second approach with the minimum set
of variables (become_method is sudo by default and
become_user is root by default).

Change-Id: Iac16f49b514f41684b319e3d091b52513f721b55
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Pin setuptools == 18.5

Yesterday the new versions of setuptools (18.6 and 18.6.1) were released
where some functionality such as installation in the editable mode was
broken. It will be fixed in the 18.6.2 release.

Change-Id: Id19879c788efbba6c6e72fe6a4a97418df124525
Partial-Bug: #1519727

commit_message:
Add synchronizer for policies and rules

This synchronizer keeps the policy engine's policies and rules in sync with
the database.  With this change, Congress should be able to run policy engine
replicas side-by-side in an high-availability configuration.

Implements blueprint: basic-high-availability
Change-Id: I72d8a9952d8345129656c4a701896614fa837a08

commit_message:
Modularize inventory and add initial testing

The inventory module for bifrost is a vital component, however
as it was developed as a single file and it needs to to be broken
up into a modular chunk in order to have meaningful testing.

Broke into module, symlinking the file into place for now until
documentation and install process can be updated.

Added two basic tests to lay the groundwork for basic testing
of the data parsing and result passing.

Change-Id: I02e79b635202a7933ae641b9d27cc19a75b7bc4f
Partial-Bug: 1499801

I wonder if we should also automatically stream images if (image size) > (ram size)'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-11-17 14:03:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Jim.

The logic there can get pretty complicated, see JayF comments on [1] about disk vs network speed.

Also, not all images can be streamed, e.g, qcow2 format can not be streamed because it first needs to be converted to raw and the process to convert it needs random access different parts of the file (making it impossible to pipe, because it's not sequential).

Another thing would be "ram size", cause since the ramdisk is loaded in the ram it gets a bit complicated to calculate how much of the ram is actually available that can be used to cache the image prior to writing it to the disk.

And also the tmpfs itself, it never uses 100% of the ram. By default tmpfs are created with half of the size of the physical ram [2], so it depends on the base OS that IPA is running to tweak it for us.

So, I think that having a switch to disable/enable it for raw images is good cause it makes things simpler.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/234339/
[2] https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/filesystems/tmpfs.txt (see the "size" parameter)'}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-11-17 14:07:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

We'll also need to update this check to allow for large images to be deployed at all: https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/drivers/modules/agent.py#L145"}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2015-11-17 14:08:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(oh, and I should have mentioned I'm okay with not automatically deciding whether or not to cache, was just throwing the idea out there) :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-17 15:07:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

[{'created': '2015-11-17 12:22:51.000000000', 'message': 'Add switch to enable/disable streaming raw images for IPA

This patch is adding a configuration option called "stream_raw_images"
under the "agent" group. By default this option is set to True, meaning
that the IPA ramdisk will be instructed to stream raw images directly
onto the disk instead of copying it to a tmpfs partition prior of
writing it to the disk. By streaming raw images IPA will consume less
memory to run and the deployment will be faster (unless the disk being
deployed is really slow).

Depends-On: Iddf67907bc9b54bbd3065a97064cb5a3602cfe18
Related-Bug: #1505685
Change-Id: I7e7ed7e7aeebbf7c936605a72aa974db2123a43e

This patch is adding a configuration option called "stream_raw_images"
under the "agent" group. By default this option is set to True, meaning
that the IPA ramdisk will be instructed to stream raw images directly
onto the disk instead of copying it to a tmpfs partition prior of
writing it to the disk. By streaming raw images IPA will consume less
memory to run and the deployment will be faster (unless the disk being

commit_message:
Add switch to enable/disable streaming raw images for IPA

This patch is adding a configuration option called "stream_raw_images"
under the "agent" group. By default this option is set to True, meaning
that the IPA ramdisk will be instructed to stream raw images directly
onto the disk instead of copying it to a tmpfs partition prior of
writing it to the disk. By streaming raw images IPA will consume less
memory to run and the deployment will be faster (unless the disk being
deployed is really slow).

Depends-On: Iddf67907bc9b54bbd3065a97064cb5a3602cfe18
Related-Bug: #1505685
Change-Id: I7e7ed7e7aeebbf7c936605a72aa974db2123a43e

commit_message:
Bug  :  Not able to create a resource without sync attribute

description : when user just want to check the limit of quota,
without sync attribute,function gives error.

DocImpact
closes-Bug:1455346
Implements: blueprint Adding cinder qutoa to limit per volume size
Change-Id: I910b5bf8ab936272d793fa8cce9d14e5f1674816

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-18 11:09:22.000000000', 'message': "Fix metadata retrieval in GPFS driver

GPFS driver was using 'volume_metadata' to get the
volume metadata. With versionedobjects, it is to be
retrieved using 'metadata' from volume.
This patch fixes the issue. It first tries for 'volume_metadata'
in the volume object, if not present, it will try for 'metadata'
to get the metadata.

Change-Id: I97649874ab54187a469193c8cae773409e9913e6
Closes-bug: 1517404
"}]
commit_message:
Fix metadata retrieval in GPFS driver

GPFS driver was using 'volume_metadata' to get the
volume metadata. With versionedobjects, it is to be
retrieved using 'metadata' from volume.
This patch fixes the issue. It first tries for 'volume_metadata'
in the volume object, if not present, it will try for 'metadata'
to get the metadata.

Change-Id: I97649874ab54187a469193c8cae773409e9913e6
Closes-bug: 1517404

[{'created': '2015-07-22 05:22:45.000000000', 'message': 'Add availability_zone support for Scheduler

This patch adds the availability_zone attribute to agents, networks
and routers, so that users can specify where network services run.

commit_message:
Revert "Rename semantic-version dep to semantic_version"

This reverts commit 3d4b27f8554baee165d9984895ca2471d88d6812.

The change is actually opposite what the commit message claims and
will set the wrong name to the requirements.

Change-Id: I1f3f50d584a163bdefbab406d8d67205614746f8

[{'created': '2015-11-13 19:29:45.000000000', 'message': 'Remove dependency on instance_info for DHCP config

According to the documentation[1], instance_info variable is used to
define the instance that will be deployed, and has nothing to do with
its networking configuration. It therefore is not sensible to only
allow static DHCP settings for nodes with instance_info defined since
"By default, this is NOT expected to be defined".

Moreover, when the new dhcp-hosts file is created in
bifrost.dhcp-hosts.d/, dnsmasq needs to re-read this directory
regardless of whether instance_info is defined, so it does not make
sense for the "Sending dnsmasq HUP" task to be dependent on
instance_info NOT being defined.

Sending HUP should be safe to do; according to the dnsmasq man page,

  When it receives a SIGHUP, dnsmasq clears its cache and then
  re-loads /etc/hosts and /etc/ethers and any file given by
  --dhcp-hostsfile, --dhcp-hostsdir, --dhcp-optsfile, --dhcp-optsdir,
  --addn-hosts or --hostsdir. The dhcp lease change script is called
  for all existing DHCP leases. If --no-poll is set SIGHUP also
  re-reads /etc/resolv.conf. SIGHUP does NOT re-read the configuration
  file."

This does not imply any disruption of service. This assumption is
consistent with a reading of the dnsmasq signal handling code[2].

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/bifrost/tree/playbooks/roles/bifrost-deploy-nodes-dynamic/README.md#n45
[2] http://bazaar.launchpad.net/~vcs-imports/dnsmasq/master/view/head:/src/dnsmasq.c#L1193

'}]
commit_message:
Remove dependency on instance_info for DHCP config

According to the documentation[1], instance_info variable is used to
define the instance that will be deployed, and has nothing to do with
its networking configuration. It therefore is not sensible to only
allow static DHCP settings for nodes with instance_info defined since
"By default, this is NOT expected to be defined".

Moreover, when the new dhcp-hosts file is created in
bifrost.dhcp-hosts.d/, dnsmasq needs to re-read this directory
regardless of whether instance_info is defined, so it does not make
sense for the "Sending dnsmasq HUP" task to be dependent on
instance_info NOT being defined.

Sending HUP should be safe to do; according to the dnsmasq man page,

  When it receives a SIGHUP, dnsmasq clears its cache and then
  re-loads /etc/hosts and /etc/ethers and any file given by
  --dhcp-hostsfile, --dhcp-hostsdir, --dhcp-optsfile, --dhcp-optsdir,
  --addn-hosts or --hostsdir. The dhcp lease change script is called
  for all existing DHCP leases. If --no-poll is set SIGHUP also
  re-reads /etc/resolv.conf. SIGHUP does NOT re-read the configuration
  file."

This does not imply any disruption of service. This assumption is
consistent with a reading of the dnsmasq signal handling code[2].

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/bifrost/tree/playbooks/roles/bifrost-deploy-nodes-dynamic/README.md#n45
[2] http://bazaar.launchpad.net/~vcs-imports/dnsmasq/master/view/head:/src/dnsmasq.c#L1193

Change-Id: Iae0dae8ad4dd7c9f2263b97875702ed0970761cf

commit_message:
Make delete_server() return True/False

To be consistent with our other delete API methods, make delete_server()
return True if the delete succeeded, or False if the server was not
deleted because it was not found.

This also combines the functional testing of create_server() and
delete_server() so that tests are more efficient by eliminating an
extra instance creation. This is in anticipation of adding more
tests that will create server instances and there are only so
many resources available in the test environment.

Change-Id: If1b1a3886df60fb064682caa23113f91b78a4090

commit_message:
VMware: Skip unsupported datastore types

vCenter supports different types of datastores such as
VMFS, NFS etc. Currently the VMDK driver supports only
vSAN, VMFS and NFS datastores for storing volume vmdks.
This patch adds a check to skip unsupported datastore
types during volume creation.

Closes-bug: #1519316

commit_message:
Add 'hw:cpu_threads_policy=separate' scheduling

The 'separate' CPU threads policy requires a host with an SMT
architecture but ensures vCPUs are allocated from non-thread siblings.
This is useful for workloads that may see performance impacts due to
contention.

Change-Id: I18b3a6413450d5f0cbc3eb8e66a2bcda23293478
Implements: blueprint virt-driver-cpu-thread-pinning

zuul: enable beaker jobs for puppet-mistral

We want to have beaker jobs for puppet-mistral so we can perform
funtional testing for the puppet module.

Updates REST & RPC abandon API with is_forced=False

Adds the is_forced parameter to abandon_stack to
allow the user to forcefully abandon the stack even
its not exported.

Fix more unhandled errors for full validation

Fix some errors that are not being handled for full validation.
They include some invalid node template and outputs property names,
and references to non-existing node templates. Also, add proper
unit tests.

commit_message:
Use sudo for role testing

There are 2 ways to realize the privilege escalation
needed for the gate jobs.

1) Editing the playbooks (and hope to not forget to
write the sudo/become lines for every role)
2) Editing the inventory and set the variable there.

I'm taking the second approach with the minimum set
of variables (become_method is sudo by default and
become_user is root by default).

Change-Id: I066ac778f7bf3d3f569791e30067bcab4e8eef6b
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
SR-IOV: Improve the vnic type check in the neutron api

The Neutronv2 API checks the vnic_type to see whether
or not it should include a PCI requests for SR-IOV ports.
The check is "if the vnic_type is not NORMAL" which is fine
for now that we have only NORMAL, DIRECT and MACVTAP, but in the future more vnic types
can be added. This patch update the check to be what the vnic types
are expecting to be.

Change-Id: I7b8ba1acfbafc3d02ab50afadf4627fcce052484

commit_message:
Adjust conditions when enable_snat is specified

Some clouds barf about policy if the enable_snat attribute is
sent during router creation. Only send it if it is different
from the default (i.e., only when False).

This is a fix for:
https://github.com/ansible/ansible-modules-core/issues/2474

Change-Id: Id656029b9cf593fcb8e0771fa19c567126c565ee

Log debug generated swift temp URLs

Debugging an IPA installation using Swift temp URLs would be
much easier if we simply logged this generated URL in
the conductor log somewhere...

commit_message:
glusterfs/volume layout: fix incorrect usage of export_location

Actually, all uses of export_location are incorrect -- from the
layout code's point of view, export_location is an arbitrary
opaque value, obtained from self.driver._setup_via_manager with
which the only legit action is to return it from create_share*.

That we use export_location as dict key in ensure_share is just
a pre-layout relict that survived by the virtue of remaining
unnoticed. Now the referred bug forced it out of the dark.

Change-Id: I965dae99486002f00145daff0cd2a848777b5b81
Partial-Bug: #1501670

commit_message:
Fix gate-nova-functional-constraints

Tox runs gerrit-git-prep, however when constraints are used
zuul-git-prep-upper-constraints must be used.  Make a new tox job
template that pulls in the required git-prep and update nova to use it.

Implements Blueprint: Requirements-Management

Change-Id: I59fcf763d7eb9252e950dce5783befc20b4e8fd4

commit_message:
Declare multiattach is True in LVMVolume driver

An LVM volume can be attached to multi instances, however,
this feature is not declared in LVMVolume driver. As a result,
if a user create a multi-attached volume using LVMVolume as
backend, they will be failed.

In this commit, we declared multiattach is True in LVMVolume
driver.

Change-Id: I66a4d62054fee14da6cf029084074453b30eb1bc

[{'account_id': 17386, 'date': '2015-11-16 18:24:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-11-16 18:24:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 17386, 'date': '2015-11-16 19:26:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 16520, 'date': '2015-11-16 19:43:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-16 20:06:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(9 comments)

I see all of the arguments laid out as have been discussed. I am very far from convinced that this is even a good idea.

Kolla deploys OpenStack, it cannot use any of the OpenStack services to do things that all the other APIs do (auth being the biggest thing). We would have to implement these things to some degree and this goes way beyond our mission statement.

We would have to have a database backend of some kind. And the API would have to be highly available. Having an API puts us in a situation to re-implement OpenStack services and having to pull a Triple-O type deal.

The fact is we have a deployment tool, not a deployment service. An API adds little or no benefit that cannot be satisfactorily duplicated by the chosen deployment tool since thats all an API will be calling anyway (either ansible or mesos).'}, {'account_id': 16520, 'date': '2015-11-16 20:22:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Sam, I think most of your comments have a similar view, and that is just hand editing file and digging through ansible output is just fine for people who want to use kolla.  This is not only a problem with kolla but openstack in general.

Kolla and openstack have a big usability problem.  It comes up in the survey from every single conference.  Maybe it isn't a problem for you because you are fine digging through code to find out why something is working the way it is.  That doesn't mean the effort shouldn't be made to make it easier for people who don't want to do that, to use.

We aren't suggesting implementing a bunch of odd stuff from scratch.  Most of the monitoring / health stuff can indeed be done through ansible, and we want to do that, but the information is deep enough that end users might not want to parse ansible output, and instead have an API which is easier to consume programatically."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-16 21:26:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

I am slightly confused by the scope of the monitoring provided by the API. The spec states it will give a view of the running cloud, but that seems like a HUGE problem which is being solved by multiple other projects? It makes more sense to me that the API would give a view into admin tasks that are running like deploy, add node, etc.  Leave the overall cloud monitoring to projects aimed directly at monitoring. Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 16520, 'date': '2015-11-17 07:25:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hey Brett, we aren't looking to be some big monitoring framework.  I think the idea is just to provide some level, above the zero that is currently in place, of visibility into the state of the deployed environment.   This would be done at request time, not something that would need to be stored in a database, and possibly collected via the ansible host / docker facts to get some view into the state of the hosts and kolla containers.

If people want a deeper or proactive view of the deployed environment I agree, other tools can do a better job of that and I wouldn't want to duplicate that kind of complexity here."}, {'account_id': 14027, 'date': '2015-11-17 08:34:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

About monitoring of cloud health - please be more concrete about what you want to use for it. The proposition we discussed before summit was Rally and/or Tempest. I'd be probably against using any other tool outside OpenStack ecosystem.

Also, I'm not sure whether monitoring / health check should be in the scope of this spec. Implementing a container with Rally runned by Ansible or Mesos sourds like a separate task IMO.

About logging - please consider using Logstash or something similar in future. I'm not sure whether we should implement too much about that by ourselves.

Don't consider this -1 as being fully against your ideas about logging and monitoring. Please share more details and convince me. ;)"}, {'account_id': 9927, 'date': '2015-11-17 14:27:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks for the explanation Borne.  I think more useful and appropriate would be a look into the status of "jobs" the admin is running using Kolla.  Something that would report for the current job: the task that is currently running, how long has it been running, how many tasks remain in the job, relevant status/output from previous tasks.  Something along those lines would keep the scope focused on Kolla.  And then with that scope in mind, only pull in the info from the running cloud required to perform those tasks (e.g. current version for upgrades, dead hypervisors that need replacing, etc).  But that info would be just for support, not the primary view.  Does that seem reasonable?'}, {'account_id': 17386, 'date': '2015-11-17 15:45:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

in-line answers to some of the comments...'}, {'account_id': 17386, 'date': '2015-11-17 18:23:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 16520, 'date': '2015-11-17 18:26:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-17 19:56:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Hey Britt.  I think what you are suggesting sounds really useful.  Currently the CLI code just kicks off ansible deploy and outputs that to the console so the user can watch the progress, and if they want finer grained output the -v flag can be used to see detailed output.   I'm not sure how hard it would be to get better programatticaly digestible data out of ansible regarding the state of the deploy, but would love to have it.

If kolla itself ends up including mechanisms to monitor the state of the hosts / containers then we of course want have that data accessible if possible via the REST api if it makes sense to do so.  We hadn't seen any real push in that direction as of the Liberty release and the lack of even a simple representation of host and container health is a big problem for anyone who wants to use kolla in production or even scaled development / test environments."}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-18 01:47:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Borne,

I can't agree with you that that is a factor in using it in production. Mainly because people use OpenStack in production today and OpenStack does not have that monitoring bit.

But regardless, that is not an API, that is a separate service entirely. Additionally we do actually have work underway for monitoring for the Mitaka cycle which has nothing to do with an API.

The arguments I see being made for an API are to consume and do things that we don't do currently, an API won't magically allow us to do those things. We should do those things _first_ then discuss an api"}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2015-11-18 12:47:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I think it was mentioned at some stage that the business logic in the CLI would be made into a library, which both the API and CLI would call into.

What would peoples thoughts be on just focusing on this library for the time being? I think people myself included are struggling with the concept of introducing a *service* to kolla, more so than questioning the value of having an API abstraction. Ansible currently gives us remote management, I'm not seeing the value of remotely controlling that from somewhere else via http.

A library provides us an API that the CLI and other GUIs can use, and removes all the nasty chicken and egg type problems that arise from deploying and managing a long running service that itself requires HA, authentication, a DB (I dont know why the spec seems to indicate it wouldn't need a DB), monitoring, etc. etc"}, {'account_id': 10787, 'date': '2015-11-18 14:30:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)'}, {'account_id': 17386, 'date': '2015-11-18 18:07:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Stepping back a bit, it might be worth a discussion of what we're trying to do here, separate from any specific implementation. The basic aim is to make it easier to create and maintain kolla environments, and without requiring the admin to be an ansible playbook expert.

kolla's major innovation is to containerize openstack services. With the introduction of containers there is currently no easy way to see the containers' status and versions. In order to get the container status, you either have to login remotely or send ansible commands to get the 'docker ps' status to every node running the services. Likewise, you'd have to do something similar to get the logs to see the reason for a failed deploy. So there should be a simple way for admins to get logs and basic status for the kolla containers. A generic monitoring tool is not being considered here. This would be a kolla-specific companion tool targeted at gathering container status only. (Let's set aside for now whether this is a push or pull model, or whether there's an agent or not.)

Upgrades can also be challenging. An admin may want to upgrade a single container, a service made up of several containers, multiple services at a time, or an entire HA zone. Admins may want to perform the upgrade in steps and verify that a particular upgrade succeeded before they move on to the next step. Having the ability to show container image versions is key so admins know what versions the containers images are running. And we should provide tools that allow them to selectively upgrade services, hosts, and/or groups without requiring them to hand-edit inventory files multiple times.

The other area of complexity in kolla is managing the properties. The properties are spread out among many files in a variety of directories. There is no simple way to view the various properties in one place. There should be the ability to easily find, view and edit (or not) the properties.

Is there an agreement that these are desirable goals?"}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-18 19:25:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

The majority of that I can get behind. I would like to start by pointing out that you don't have to be an Ansible expert to run Kolla. Kolla uses very little if any of the advanced Ansible things. That said, it is expected you understand how to use Ansible being that is how you are deploying kolla-ansible.

For kolla-mesos you would need to know mesos. If someone does kolla-puppet it would be expected that you have some familiarity with puppet.

As to the comments about monitoring containers. While that would be a nice thing to have I am not sure I view that as a requirement. For any decent monitoring solution service you will need to be monitoring the services, not the containers. For MariaDB+Galera you will be checking the health there. Monitoring RabbitMQ cluster health. Nova/Neutron/Cinder/etc provide healthchecks by monitoring rabbitmq queues. All of that monitoring would tell you if a container was down. There is no container that is running in a way that we should trust that everything is ok because the container is 'up'. They should all be monitored based on the health of the service not container status.

As to Upgrades, you are right if you want to do upgrades to just a particular range of services or servers you will have to be more familiar with Ansible (specifically limits and tags). That said we currently have the deploy code structured in a way that you can limit however you want, the upgrade code will work the same. How mesos handles this will remain to be seen, it may not be able to do selective upgrades on just a few nodes.

The augment file stuff is being greatly reduced in complexity (but not flexibility) just as soon as Ansible 2.0 lands and Kolla switches over. It was supposed to be before Liberty which is why we even have all of those 0 byte files in the first place, they were stop gaps. When 2.0 lands those files will not be required at all and youll see this perceived complexity drop substantially.

Overall I agree the goals are desirable, but I feel saying 'Ansible is hard, try this new different way we wrote' is just trading one complexity for another. Everything you mentioned can and will be implemented in Ansible (most likely before Mitaka).


For the record, programatically interacting with Ansible will require a complete re-implementation of all of the Ansible playbooks in python. There is no interface to do:
    'import ansible-playbook; ansible-playbook.run(site.yml)'
And screen scrapping Ansible output will not work since it is not stable."}, {'account_id': 16520, 'date': '2015-11-18 19:28:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(5 comments)'}, {'account_id': 16520, 'date': '2015-11-19 06:03:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 16620, 'date': '2015-11-19 09:57:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(12 comments)

I am +2 on this idea, but -1 as the spec is currently written.  I would also like to see Sam's idea of a python library encoding the logic that is currently encoded into the python cli as part of the code base."}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-24 01:11:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

sdake i think you misunderstand my "idea".

There is no way to consume ansible-playbooks without writing them in python. As in, no longer consuming the ansible-playbooks but reimplementing them in python, one task at a time.

Using subprocess would require screen scraping an unstable ansible output which, and this shouldn't need to be said, is a horrible idea.

I have yet to see anyone respond to me on this critically important implementation detail.'}, {'account_id': 18652, 'date': '2015-11-24 14:05:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

Great idea'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2015-11-25 04:46:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

My 2c, I like the "feature requests" at the top of the spec

 - improved diagnostics
 - better ways of retrieving container status
 - easier custom configuration
 
But when it comes to "the solution is a REST API", this seems odd to me. Whether something is behind an API or in a library/CLI will not effect the user and is really an implementation detail - IMHO.

As Sam has said too, as we add more deployment systems we are really going to have a situation of either 'lowest common denominator' or a huge API that no system implements well. I'd rather have a CLI that we can agree on the basics being the same but allow each system to expand as it's feature set allows (this is much messier for a REST API).'}, {'account_id': 17386, 'date': '2015-11-25 19:51:49.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Given the possibility of kolla/mesos, abandoning this for now. We'll take another look later as mesos develops."}]

commit_message:
Make bandit included in test-requirements.txt

We remove old bandit special version txt file and include it
in test-requirements.txt to make sure it can updated by global
automatically.

[{'created': '2015-11-08 21:48:25.000000000', 'message': "Port IBM storewize_svc driver to Python 3

Change default preferred node in
StorwizeSVCDriver.initialize_connection(). For fiber channel without
multipath, sort the list of nodes and pick the first node, to have a
determinist preferred node. The list of nodes is created indirectly
using list(set(nodes)) which doesn't have a determinist order. On
Python 3, the hash function is randomized, and so list(set()) has an
unknown order.

A similar change was done for volume throttling in the change
Icf7141f772397c7ac08f0f1e21ad74cb86a06351 to port the code
to Python 3.

Other changes:

* Use list(set()) in test_storwize_svc to get the expected order on
  Python 3 (the hash function is randomized on Python 3).
* StorwizeSVCDriver._check_volume_copy_ops(): replace dict.items()
  with list(dict.items()) to iterate on items. On Python 3,
  dict.items() now returns a view instead of a copy. The loop
  modifies the dictionary and a dict must not be modified while
  iterating on it, we really need a copy of items.
* StorwizeHelpers: replace a/b with a//b to use integer division on
  Python 3.
* tests-py3.txt: add cinder.tests.unit.test_storwize_svc

Change-Id: I534a85928816d6cce921545e1820311aedd1b884

commit_message:
Port IBM storewize_svc driver to Python 3

Change default preferred node in
StorwizeSVCDriver.initialize_connection(). For fiber channel without
multipath, pick the first node from the list of sorted nodes, to have
a determinist preferred node. The list of nodes is created indirectly
using list(set(nodes)) which doesn't have a determinist order. On
Python 3, the hash function is randomized, and so list(set()) has an
unknown order.

A similar change was done for volume throttling in the change
Icf7141f772397c7ac08f0f1e21ad74cb86a06351 to port the code
to Python 3.

Other changes:

* Use assertSetEqual() in test_storwize_svc to compare
  initiator_target_map, because conn_wwpns has a random order on
  Python 3.
* StorwizeSVCDriver._check_volume_copy_ops(): replace dict.items()
  with list(dict.items()) to iterate on items. On Python 3,
  dict.items() now returns a view instead of a copy. The loop
  modifies the dictionary and a dict must not be modified while
  iterating on it, we really need a copy of items.
* StorwizeHelpers: replace a/b with a//b to use integer division on
  Python 3.
* tests-py3.txt: add cinder.tests.unit.test_storwize_svc

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I534a85928816d6cce921545e1820311aedd1b884

commit_message:
Use oslo_config new type PortOpt for port options

The oslo_config library provides new type PortOpt to validate the
range of port now.

Note, rpc_zmq_max_port is a socket port upper limit, so leave it untouched.

Change-Id: Icac28141bcb09e2b894662de1a6497766351919d
Closes-Bug: #1518256
ref: https://github.com/openstack/oslo.config/blob/2.6.0/oslo_config/cfg.py#L1114

commit_message:
Make zuul-git-prep-upper-constraints safe for post

Extend zuul-git-prep-upper-constraints to infer a target branch from
$ZUUL_REFNAME when $ZUUL_BRANCH is not present. This works around
the absence of branch guidance for ref-updated triggers in post
pipeline jobs, where Zuul is not told a branch but Gerrit instead
uses the branch as the refname for the event.

Change-Id: I3fd06cc1f09847f6731f80deb00fd1515f0106e9

[{'created': '2015-07-16 15:31:18.000000000', 'message': "Add 'hw:cpu_threads_policy=avoid' filtering

Add support for the the 'avoid' CPU threads policy filter. This is

commit_message:
Add 'hw:cpu_threads_policy=avoid' filtering

The 'avoid' CPU threads policy prevents guests from being scheduled
onto hosts utilising SMT technologies, such as Intel Hyper-Threading
Technology. SMT provides performance benefits, but comes at the cost
of reduced determinism. This makes it unsuitable for some workloads
were such determinism is critical, e.g. NFV.

Add support for this 'avoid' CPU threads policy filter. This is
achieved through the use of the NUMA topology filter.

Change-Id: I7fc87755e1035bd5dd31bfd334213e41829bea2d
Implements: blueprint virt-driver-cpu-thread-pinning

commit_message:
Remove AuxAddresses from the required properties

This patch removes AuxAddresses in IPv4Data and IPv6Data in the request
against /NetworkDriver.CreateNetwork. It can not be given if it's not
specified by the CLI rather than it's set to an empty JSON object.

Change-Id: I5a36fa78adee09d91c19d533bfcf660109a0ec21
Signed-off-by: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1519260

commit_message:
Add Warning when we cannot notify

Calling Notifier.audit() won't work with LogDriver as the
logger does not have a audit level anymore, So let's at
least not fail silently and let the operators know that
we are dropping stuff on the floor.

Closes-Bug: #1518170
Change-Id: I74002c72e6763ea8b5df7d97d722619bd4a1950b

commit_message:
Default for root_helper config

This sets the default for root_helper config to the value used
by ironic: 'sudo ironic-rootwrap /etc/ironic/rootwrap.conf'.

The logic was changed a bit so as not to pass root_helper or
run_as_root arguments to processutils.execute() unless they
had been specified or needed to be passed.

Change-Id: I8cf8c07102d0a8bd4fff14afc8c2f9db6beeb949
Fixes-Bug: #1519870

commit_message:
Print the JJB template name in devstack jobs

There are a lot of devstack jobs based on a lot of very similarly
named templates.  Have the jobs print out the template name at the
start to make tracking down the actual definition easier.

Change-Id: I059735cfc7f9cd43a81650675917bdc8c3d129f5
Depends-On: I1cfed9c27a58b45ba48aeed04839bfc8f54a831e

commit_message:
Fix resource leak in test_compute

Depending on the time between the create_server() and
delete_server() calls, it's possible the delete does not
actually find the server we want to delete, so we leave
instances hanging around after our tests. Fix this by waiting
for the servers with wait=True to create_server().

Change-Id: I908fdb94dcf5e410597a7cd3ecc6c962f2bfbce3

commit_message:
Declare multiattach is True in RBD driver

An RBD volume can be attached to multi instances, however,
this feature is not declared in RBD driver. As a result,
if a user create a multi-attached volume using RBD as
backend, they will be failed.

In this commit, we declared multiattach is True in RBD
driver.

Change-Id: I70c2c0528d9c00629f9cf34d79262a5bf4750e34
Closes-Bug: #1519227

commit_message:
Clean up compute functional tests

Although the server names being created were actually unique
across tests, this change will make the test_compute.py code
more consistent with other functional test code by creating
a server name prefix string with getUniqueString(). This also
opens the door for use across new tests.

It also changes the server cleanup code to just call
delete_server() with the name of the instance for the test.
Since tests can run in parallel, we don't want to delete an
instance with a similar name out from under some other test.

Change-Id: I1b0dc3f2759f77b7d420e45b3a7a2730868e6eb0

commit_message:
Unexpected exception on tox test output on non-error

When the co-routine invoked by the event_simulator throws an exception
it was being spit out to the stdout. This exception on a non-error is
confusing. The proposed change will enable an exception handler in the
event_simulator (which was commented out) and catch the exception and
push it to the log file.

Change-Id: I7633ded724f30836b2c5bd471d305f57ab04ce4d
Closes-Bug: #1378083

The problem here relates to the way in which Trove handles the rename of the user and not the privilege clearing action. It is hard to put the details here, will put them in the bug instead.'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-12-02 17:28:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-2

I guess that's the wrong thing to do; I should put the comments here.

The issue is in the way in which trove is handling the rename; this is leaving bad data in information schema.

This is what trove does to rename a user.

UPDATE mysql.user SET User='charlie' WHERE User = 'bravo' AND Host = '%'

Since there are no RI constraints on the information schema and mysql system database, this leaves turds in information schema, turds which come back to bite us when a new user is created with the old name.

The correct way to rename a user is

http://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.0/en/rename-user.html

RENAME USER bravo TO charlie

This updates information schema correctly."}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2014-12-02 17:33:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Here is the complete sequence of operations ...

trove database-create 56fde5de-1cc3-480e-b0a6-6683cbf75ea2 tango-db
trove user-create 56fde5de-1cc3-480e-b0a6-6683cbf75ea2 tango tango-password --databases tango-db

MySQL [(none)]> select grantee, table_schema from information_schema.schema_privileges where privilege_type != 'USAGE' and table_schema = 'tango-db' group by grantee, table_schema;
+-------------+--------------+
| grantee     | table_schema |
+-------------+--------------+
| 'tango'@'%' | tango-db     |
+-------------+--------------+
1 row in set (0.01 sec)

trove user-update-attributes 56fde5de-1cc3-480e-b0a6-6683cbf75ea2 tango --new_name uniform

MySQL [(none)]> select grantee, table_schema from information_schema.schema_privileges where privilege_type != 'USAGE' and table_schema = 'tango-db' group by grantee, table_schema;
+---------------+--------------+
| grantee       | table_schema |
+---------------+--------------+
| 'tango'@'%'   | tango-db     |
| 'uniform'@'%' | tango-db     |
+---------------+--------------+
2 rows in set (0.00 sec)

MySQL [(none)]>

On the other hand, if you were to properly use rename ...

MySQL [(none)]> select grantee, table_schema from information_schema.schema_privileges where privilege_type != 'USAGE' and table_schema = 'victor-db' group by grantee, table_schema;
+--------------+--------------+
| grantee      | table_schema |
+--------------+--------------+
| 'victor'@'%' | victor-db    |
+--------------+--------------+
1 row in set (0.01 sec)

MySQL [(none)]> rename user victor to whiskey;
Query OK, 0 rows affected (0.00 sec)

MySQL [(none)]> select grantee, table_schema from information_schema.schema_privileges where privilege_type != 'USAGE' and table_schema = 'victor-db' group by grantee, table_schema;
+---------------+--------------+
| grantee       | table_schema |
+---------------+--------------+
| 'whiskey'@'%' | victor-db    |
+---------------+--------------+
1 row in set (0.00 sec)"}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2014-12-03 04:35:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

so, the suggested way to work out is to use rename command instead of table updations.'}, {'account_id': 5293, 'date': '2014-12-03 08:01:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

Reasons:
- While using update-user-attributes to change the user's name or host access
  the old access to the databases remain as it is.
- There is a need to remove those old access so that any new user created with
  identical name does not get that previous existing access.

Changes:
- Added the query to delete the needful records from mysql.db for database access
- Executing the access-clearing query while update-user-attributes
  if either of user name or host is update.

Change-Id: Id87da96363d3cb932e6a92a611eebb054897a409

commit_message:
Updates the update_user_attributes functionality

Reasons:
- While using update-user-attributes to change the user's name
  or host access the old access to the databases is left behind.
- The correct way to update user or host name is to use RENAME USER.

Changes:
- Updated statements to use "RENAME USER" for renaming the
  username or hostname.
- Updated statements to use "SET PASSWORD FOR" for changing passwords.
- Unit tests updated for sql_query.py
- Integration tests added to test the intended functionality for
  (user/host)-name updation.

Change-Id: Id87da96363d3cb932e6a92a611eebb054897a409
Closes-Bug: #1380880

commit_message:
Update: clean keepalived and radvd instances after pcs cluster stop

Older neutron versions have a bug which makes them leave keepalived and
radvd running even after all neutron services are stopped, preventing
neutron router failover from happening. Router can then get stuck on the
inactive node, like this:

[stack@instack ~]$ neutron l3-agent-list-hosting-router default_router
+--------------------------------------+------------------------------------+----------------+-------+----------+
| id                                   | host                               | admin_state_up | alive | ha_state |
+--------------------------------------+------------------------------------+----------------+-------+----------+
| 48ca9477-b93b-4305-9e6d-9f1c5d3388f0 | overcloud-controller-1.localdomain | True           | :-)   | standby  |
| eba0575c-654f-4da6-b1cd-f7fdf1cd3726 | overcloud-controller-2.localdomain | True           | :-)   | standby  |
| 68815390-251f-4425-a5f8-38bdbf3bdb90 | overcloud-controller-0.localdomain | True           | xxx   | active   |
+--------------------------------------+------------------------------------+----------------+-------+----------+

We need to kill the leftover processes manually to prevent the state
described above from happening.

See https://review.gerrithub.io/#/c/248931

Change-Id: I2deaa176222983daa0c33ab52a6aa5dbe7365302

commit_message:
Corrects INCLUDE_MARKER_OPERATORS for MySQL

Reasons:
- Currently the value of INCLUDE_MARKER_OPERATORS[True] means ">=".
- Because of this when matching the database name it results in
  name >= value, which results in more than needed values and
  the sorting mechanism then may return the other value similar
  to one matched as explained in bug.

Changes:
- Corrects the value for INCLUDE_MARKER_OPERATORS[True] means ">="
  to INCLUDE_MARKER_OPERATORS[True] means "=",
  so that only matched value is returned.
- Updated the tests for matching the resulting query.

Change-Id: Ia197b007917f1b5f9f681e0d2d749489235052be
Closes-Bug: #1316717

commit_message:
Add percona int-test group

Reasons:
 - As you know, Percona is another flavor of MySQL
   community distro, and in Trove its integration
   part works with shared mysql driver.

Change-Id: I2b793506ac577953b0094a68205f56a4df765ff2
Closes-Bug: #1417518

commit_message:
User management for Vertica clusters and instances

As the spec specifies, changes were made to enable user
CRUD operations for Vertica clusters and instances.n the trove
client. Depending on whether its an instance or a cluster, the
user operations are performed. Unit tests for the user
operations for clusters are also added.

Implements blueprint: cluster-user-management

Change-Id: Ic6367bae2f2cf8f3cfea4b858376e1073d8b6fbc

nova schedulers.

This will make git review workflow work within this role
This will also prevent undesired files.

I believe this approach is fundamentally wrong.  It effectively says that the taskmanager should wait almost indefinitely on a mysql operation that should never take more than a few seconds, because the same cloud has a big data database where the same operation could take hours.

The better solution is to ensure that the taskmanager uses the appropriate timeout for the datastore on which it is operating.'}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-03-23 15:49:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

How did you find that this patchset is making it indefinite wait.

I tried to make it datastore specific, the usage_timeout.
Please let me know if I am missing something.

What I want to achieve through this patchset is to make the usage_timeout dependent on the datastore whose guest is needed to be booted.'}, {'account_id': 9782, 'date': '2015-03-25 18:32:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: -Code-Review

Sushil, thank you for making the changes and I am giving a +1 for the time being. I noticed in an earlier patch Morgan had mentioned that it was confusing to use the same names (usage_timeout) for the default parameter and datastore specific ones (which is why I am assuming you renamed the datastore specific ones). I may have missed something that caught Morgan's eyes. My reasoning for using the same name was that both the parameters did the same thing, so it seemed confusing to name them different. I could be wrong. Open to other thoughts. Thank you."}, {'account_id': 13355, 'date': '2015-04-11 17:18:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 9782, 'date': '2015-04-13 14:04:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10215, 'date': '2015-04-13 20:30:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

This will be the third time we've changed this in just over a year.  We've gone from having one value to datastore specific, to a hybrid (datastore/default that may not have been implemented correctly) to now having a default, plus a value in each datastore.  I'd like to make sure we don't revisit this again.

My vote is to have a default 'usage_timeout' in the main section that can be overridden in each datastore specific section.  That would mean that all datastores that are ok with a usage_timeout of 600 should not have an entry in their respective sections.  (Basically, it's what's implemented here, just with a whole bunch of redundant entries in each datastore that could be removed).

-1 to provoke some more thoughts ..."}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-04-14 04:25:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(3 comments)

Would welcome the thoughts'}, {'account_id': 15090, 'date': '2015-04-14 17:55:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10295, 'date': '2015-04-15 10:01:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

I agree with Peter on the fact that if a datastore is good with the default usage_timeout, it doesnt need to add it again in its options.'}, {'account_id': 10440, 'date': '2015-04-15 16:03:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

I am not against the notion that it should be deprecated, I just wrote what was suggested/decided in the meeting that keep the default as well as the datastore-specific.

So, if we have a vote here that we want to get rid of usage_timeout from default configuration, I can proceed for that.'}, {'account_id': 10215, 'date': '2015-04-27 18:34:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Here's the problem - Petr and I looked at the logs for the meeting (http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-meeting-alt/%23openstack-meeting-alt.2015-03-25.log) and came up with the following:

  2015-03-25T18:46:45  <SlickNik> So 1. Short term, I think datastore specifc timeouts falling back to default makes sense.
  ... <snip> ...
  2015-03-25T18:55:06  <amrith> #action sushilkm to make usage_timeout and cluster_timeout datastore specific

So both implementations were 'agreed' on.  I personally am fine with either.  I have a slight preference to having them defined in each datastore without a default, since that's how everything else works, but having a default is ok too.  In the case of having a default though, the option should be left out of datastore sections where the value is determined to be the same as the default value.
To clarify, what I would like to see is either remove the default, or remove all the datastore specific configs where the value is the same as the default.  (If we keep the default, might be good to change the help message to something like: 'Default maximum time (in seconds) to wait for a Guest to become active.')"}, {'account_id': 10215, 'date': '2015-04-27 18:38:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Maybe we should vote ... if so, here's mine (100 point votes):

  Datastore-specific only, no default: 60
  Datastore-specific, with default: 40"}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-04-28 02:01:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
Use datastore specific timeouts if they exists

Reasons:
- If one taskmanager is managing multiple datastores it becomes
  mandatory to setup the usage_timeout/cluster_usage_timeout
  to be the highest value to accommodate highest time-taking datastore.

Changes:
- Updates taskamanager to use datastore-specific usage_timeout,
  if one exists, otherwise use the default one.
- Updates mongodb and vertica cluster strategies to use
  datastore-specific cluster_usage_timeout, if one exists,
  otherwise use the default one.
- Updated usage_timeout from mysql and percona confs to be 600,
  as the integration tests do not work with previous value of 400 seconds.

Closes-Bug: #1432558
Closes-Bug: #1469989
Change-Id: If78dead1ea013ed7a807b4a9327056092ff7012a

commit_message:
Stop using nova client in test_compute

The test_compute functional test code was using nova client
directly instead of the shade API. Let's avoid that.

Change-Id: Iac5650a036f006cf3d30ff44086d348cba7c303f
