(10 comments)

at a high level, I see no reason why the cluster users API cannot be a simple extension of the instance users API.

i.e. where the instance users API is 

/v1.0/{tenant-id}/instance/{id}/users/...

this should be

/v1.0/{tenant-id}/cluster/{id}/users/

Yet, this specification proposes an API that is materially different from its instance equivalent which is confusing, to say the least.

The paths are differently constructed, the methods are different, and the return codes are also materially different. While the users API for instances is largely asynchronous, this API appears to be synchronous.

The spec is also incomplete in that for each API it fails to list the response codes.'}, {'account_id': 9664, 'date': '2015-11-25 18:54:04.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

abandoning for inactivity.'}]

commit_message:
User management for Vertica clusters and instances

As the spec specifies, changes were made to
enable user CRUD operations for Vertica clusters
and instances.

To associate a user with a cluster, changes to the
user api. The previous UserController was replaced
with a DatastoreUserController interface that the
VerticaUserController and the MySQLUserController
both implement. The interface has methods for
managing users on both instances and clusters.

Change-Id: I21ebdc8e6ae896ad8241ad296fbb07db862cfd72
Implements blueprint: cluster-user-management

About configuration attribute names:

  cfg.StrOpt('config_server_ram_quota', default='768')
  cfg.StrOpt('query_router_ram_quota', default='768')

and

  cfg.IntOpt('config_server_disk_size_quota', default='5')  
  cfg.IntOpt('query_router_disk_size_quota', default='5')


Lookup mechanis for flavors:
1. Pick quotas.
2. Find flavor with picked quotas.
3. If there's no such, look for closest one.
4. If p.#3 got failed:
4.1 Reject provisioning request.
4.1 (alternative) Create needed flavor. With each new provisioning created flavor would be used.


Since it's in WIP i'm voting with '0' until K trunk would be opened."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-27 21:05:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Updating with discussion at mid-cycle from etherpad at https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/trove-kilo-sprint-blueprints-bugs

1. Needs spec in RST format

2. There are three, or maybe four different levels of implementation. The first would be the hard-coded configuration(s) as proposed here, the next would be a configuration parameter with some default in the code, the third would be an API to specify this (as part of the create call) and finally having the API support a way to specifiy it with an override as a configuration parameter and a default. We believe that even a configuration parameter would be an improvement over a hard-coded specification.

3. We feel that with a spec, and an implementation that has a configuration parameter with an override in the code, this will be ready for review.'}, {'account_id': 5293, 'date': '2015-04-01 10:16:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Workflow-1 Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Custom Flavors For Config Servers and Routers

adds configurations for setting config-server flavor as well
as the query-router flavor for mongodb clusters. prior to this
patch, the routers and config-servers would inherit the flavor
chosen for the instances, which is an extremely inefficient
use of resources.

Change-Id: Iac0803401c30141f5e9d9544bf982597647092d9
Implements: blueprint clustering-sizing

commit_message:
Use native Heat template format and resources

This patch starts to move Trove usage of Heat to native Heat templates
and OpenStack resources.

Changes include:
- use native HOT syntax for the template
- use native HOT functions to resolve resources and parameters
- use native OpenStack volume and volume attachment resources
- use native OpenStack server resource

As a consequence of the latter, Trove images no longer should require
heat-cfntools package, boot config is done purely via cloud-init.
*Warning* - the default login name to the instance might no longer
be 'ec2-user' and depends on actual cloud image used.

The resources left untouched are security group and floating ip plus
association as currently in Heat only those AWS-compat resources
support both Nova-network and Neutron backends transparently.

Change-Id: I9bcdf234ccd3881f1ab836542c689da44d592e1c
Implements: blueprint native-os-heat-resources

When glance is ready, I would be happy to see us migrate to using it as our metadata service.'}, {'account_id': 971, 'date': '2014-07-24 14:20:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

+1 Iccha.  The reason why I kept the entrypoint to metadata so small was so that whenever there was an official metadata service in openstack it could be easily moved in.'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-07-24 15:27:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Code-Review-1

As i can see, from Trove perspective - metadata is not critical feature (IMHO out of scope of Database program, we should remain being Data-plane API instead of becoming data-source API). So we should wait until Glance devs would implement it instead of writing something proprietary. We should focus on reviewing https://review.openstack.org/#/c/98554 to find out if Metadata Catalog covers all cases. But i don't see Metadata CRUD operation as part of Trove API at all.


Even if somehow it gets merged - when Glance Metadata Catalog will land we would need to deprecate all metadata API since it would be cross-project overlap.

Few words about "Goals" section - storing "critical" data inside backend in plain-text form seems to be a huge security issue.

So, we have to re-consider use cases for Metadata API and apply them to Glance Metadata Catalog.


Icca, another cross-project integration, i've been waiting for lifecycle pluggins in Heat for, at least, like 3 month. And that's the only one reason why we don't have full-functional support for Heat resource management.
And we should follow the same behaviour pattern with Metadata.'}, {'account_id': 694, 'date': '2014-07-24 15:57:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Code-Review-2

(7 comments)

This looks great and I can't wait to see it land in Trove. I just have the following two issues with it.

1) There are also two exception types which are added but unused.

2) "test_metadata_controller" is basically a bunch of integration tests. That's what the actual integration tests are for. Because they run in fake mode, which already has its own setup code and mocks, having a bunch of different setup code to essentially be able to run code end-to-end (this code goes from the controller to model to view and back again after-all) is duplication. This is actually a widespread problem I'd like to see us stop doing as it makes it harder to refactor the code later, since all these low-level details are wired up in individual "unit" tests which are actually testing the majority of the Trove stack and thus depend on incidental things that aren't the focus of what's under test.

Regarding Denis's comments, I agree with Iccha and Daniel that waiting for a feature thats at the spec stage in Glance is a bad idea. I also am not sure I like the concept of having to call an external service every single time we need metadata. We already have to call Nova all the time to figure out the instance status. I also think we need to spend less time worrying about what other projects in OpenStack might do in the future and more adding the features we need to Trove.'}, {'account_id': 2559, 'date': '2014-07-24 20:32:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 17.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-24 20:32:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

commit_message:
Add instance metadata functionality to trove

Instance metadata is a feature that has been requested frequently by
Trove users. They need a way to store critical information for their
instances and have that be associated with the instance so that it is
displayed whenever that instance is listed via the API.

This also becomes very usable from a testing perspective when doing
integration/CI. The metadata can be utilized to store things like what
process created the instance, what the instance is being used for, etc.

The following calls have been implemented to facilitate metadata
support:

  create
  delete
  list
  show
  edit
  update

Implements: blueprint trove-metadata

Author: Daniel Salinas <imsplitbit@gmail.com>

Co-Authored-By: Joe Cruz <joe.cruz@rackspace.com>
Co-Authored-By: Denis Makogon <dmakogon@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Peter Stachowski <peter@tesora.com>

Change-Id: I1925b58b0ead307babe57d0ee28dcb5449fd6ce5

Some comments on models.py are attached to the file.

Also some comments/questions regarding the change and the commit message. The commit message says 

"But if heat provisioning is enabled, Trove should check status of its Instance and status of Stack, because checking status of Compute instance only is not enough, since Stack contains more than one resource."

According to the code, if heat is enabled all we're checking is status of instance. This is not consistent with (what I understand of) the commit message.

The commit message further says, 

"Since taskmanager waiting for stack status 'CREATE_COMPLETE'/'CREATE_FAILED' at provisioning, no need to pull Compute Instance status inside method _service_is_active method. Just need to poll Trove Instance status."

In fact the method _service_is_active() does poll compute instance status using a function _check_if_compute_instance_is_in_valid_state()

Finally, commit message states that 

"Changes: - splitting _service_is_active into: - trove_instance_is_active; - _compute_instance_is_active. - updating poll_intil retriever when heat provisioning enabled."

In fact the code uses the names  _check_trove_instance_is_in_valid_state and _check_if_compute_instance_is_in_valid_state, both of which I submit are less accurate than the ones proposed in the commit message.'}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-06-18 08:49:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I think this is better than before but I'm still dubious about the places where these checks for status are being made. Thanks for changing the method names as I'd requested in earlier patch sets.

As a consequence of the abstractions proposed , there are now also going to be redundant _log_and_raise() invocations that are less than ideal.

I get the premise: a call to create_instance can result either in a call to _create_server_volume_heat, a call to _create_server_volume or a call to _create_server_volume_individually.

_create_server_volume_heat takes care of its own stack polling and stuff.

_create_server_volume directly calls nova_client.servers.create() and handles the call to _verify_compute_instance_is_active() right there.

Finally, _create_server_volume_individually() calls _create_server which calls calls nova_client.servers.create(). However, _create_server_volume_individually is the one that is checking for _verify_compute_instance_is_active().

In the event that the instance fails to go active, _verify_compute_instance_is_active will call _log_and_raise().

The callers, _create_server_volume and _create_server_volume_individually both call _log_and_raise() as well. Along the way, there are several calls to update_db().

On the whole, I feel that if we are restructuring this code and making the calling sequences more straightforward, we should make sure we understand whose responsibility it is to detect the failure, whose responsibility it is to log it and so on.

Finally while there is all this logging and stuff in handling the instance status, there is barely any logging of errors detected in _check_trove_instance_is_active(). If a timeout occurs, we log an error (no exception) and the catch all logs the exception."}, {'account_id': 694, 'date': '2014-07-25 17:31:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Please rename "_check_trove_instance_is_active" to "_check_service_is_active".

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-02 10:48:35.000000000', 'message': "Fix poll_until retriever when heat provisioning is enabled

Reasons:
 - When instance is being launched Trove-Taskmanager tries
   to define Trove instance status and Compute Instance status.
   But if heat provisioning is enabled, Trove should check status
   of its Instance and status of Stack, because checking status of
   Compute instance only is not enough, since Stack contains
   more than one resource.
 - Since taskmanager waiting for stack status
   'CREATE_COMPLETE'/'CREATE_FAILED' at provisioning,
   no need to pull Compute Instance status inside method
   _service_is_active method.
   Just need to poll Trove Instance status.

Changes:
 - splitting _service_is_active into:
   - trove_instance_is_active;
   - _compute_instance_is_active.
 - updating poll_intil retriever when heat provisioning enabled.

Change-Id: I63cfde596c15208563640d199f1d4a50bc1db668
Closes-Bug: #1325512

Reasons:
 - When instance is being launched Trove-Taskmanager tries
   to define Trove instance status and Compute Instance status.
   But if heat provisioning was enabled, Trove should check status
   of its Instance only since _create_server_volume_heat finishes

   Compute Instance status at all.

   - _check_trove_instance_is_in_valid_state;

commit_message:
Fix poll_until retriever while creating an instance

Reasons:
 - When instance is being launched Trove-Taskmanager tries
   to define Trove instance status and Compute Instance status.
   But if heat provisioning was enabled, Trove should check status
   of its Instance only since _create_server_volume_heat finishes
   with stack that's already in appropriate state - no need to check
   Compute Instance status at all.
 - Since taskmanager waiting for stack status
   'CREATE_COMPLETE'/'CREATE_FAILED' at provisioning,
   no need to pull Compute Instance status inside poll_until, because
   for heat-based provisioning is enough to poll
   and verify Instance Service status;
 - Taskmanager should block following provisioning
    steps of received compute instance is not ACTIVE.

Changes:
 - removing _service_is_active method;
 - splitting _service_is_active into:
   - _check_trove_instance_is_active;
   - _check_compute_instance_is_active.
 - updating _create_server method to poll compute instance status
   until it's ACTIVE or fail with appropriate exception;
 - updating poller to ask only for Trove instance status after
   stack/instance was created and in ACTIVE state.
 - _verify_compute_instance_is_active method was added to:
   - _create_server_volume;
   - _create_server_volume_individually;

Change-Id: I63cfde596c15208563640d199f1d4a50bc1db668
Closes-Bug: #1325512

Diving even deeper I have some alternate solutions to address this.

This is the current code in question under service.py

username, hostname = unquote_user_host(user_id)
access = models.User.access(context, instance_id, username,
    hostname)
databases = [db.name for db in access.databases]
if id not in databases:
    raise exception.DatabaseNotFound(uuid=id)
models.User.revoke(context, instance_id, username, 
	hostname, id)
return wsgi.Result(None, 202)

Alternate solution 1:
1. Get list of all database names on the mysql database based on the instance_id that was passed in 
2. Validate that the database name (id) passed in is in that list. If it is not then this is where you Raise the original exception.DatabaseNotFound(uuid=id)
3. Call the original code path because we know the database exists at this point.
4. Either return wsgi.Result(None, 202) because the user already doesn't have access and there is no reason to call revoke or raise an exception because it can be a no op, or raise a different exception such as raise 422 Unprocessable Entity with message "User doesn't have access to this database"
access = models.User.access(context, instance_id, username, hostname)        
databases = [db.name for db in access.databases]
which just got the list of databases the particular username had access to.

Prototype of new code path

if not user:
    LOG.error(_("No such user: %(user)s ") % {'user': user})
    raise exception.UserNotFound(uuid=user)
# get list of all database names here

databases = [db.name for db in access.databases]
if id not in databases:
    #either return wsgi.Result(None, 202) because the user already doesn't have access and there is no reason to call revoke or #raise an exception because it can be a no op or raise a different exception such as raise 422 Unprocessable Entity with message "User doesn't have access to this database"
models.User.revoke(context, instance_id, username, hostname, id)
return wsgi.Result(None, 202)

Alternate solution 2: 
- Remove all of this code:
username, hostname = unquote_user_host(user_id)
access = models.User.access(context, instance_id, username,
    hostname)
databases = [db.name for db in access.databases]
if id not in databases:
    raise exception.DatabaseNotFound(uuid=id)
- Call directly into models.User.revoke and ensure that the revoke_access method on the MySqlAdmin class throws the appropriate error codes. Then the delete method doesn't have to be in charge of doing all the validation and can put it off to the model to do the work and bubble up the exception. Also means that if the person calling the revoke method doesn't have access to the MySql database we would get a 403 forbidden, if the database name provided in the URI doesn't exist on the mysql instance it would be a 404, and finally if the user we are trying to revoke already doesn't have access we can either return a success since the user is already technically "removed" because they didn't have access in the first place or we can raise something a BadRequest with a message stating the user you are trying to revoke doesn't have access.'}, {'account_id': 13355, 'date': '2015-02-11 22:42:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I still believe we should throw the original access denied. The user does not have rights to revoke access - that's exactly what is going on. The administrator may not be aware of the lack of rights and we should not hide it. The fact that the rights do not need to be revoked is secondary. But that's only my opinion..."}, {'account_id': 13355, 'date': '2015-02-12 21:01:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

We need to define user here. There is the caller of the method and the user_id that is inputed in the method which the caller is trying to revoke. The person making the REST call does need to have access to the database and permissions to call the revoke command. If he did not access to call revoke on the database then yes we should raise a 403 Forbidden. That is not the case in this code. The person calling this method is trying to revoke someone else from access to a database. 

We have two cases that can happen:

1. The database name that is inputed doesn't exist or is mistyped in the request thus Raising a 404 Not Found exception because it's a routing error.

2. The user_id that is inputed never had access to the database in the first place thus we do not need to call the revoke method. In this case the caller of the method has been confirmed that he can make the call but there is no need to because the inputed user_id already has been removed because they never had access in the first place. This is why it can be a no op. If we wanted to raise an exception in this case the error code would be a 422 Unprocessable Entity which is defined as The request was well-formed but was unable to be followed due to semantic errors. The semantic errors in this case are the incorrect user_id passed in that never had access to the database the caller is trying to revoke them from."}, {'account_id': 14576, 'date': '2015-02-17 17:30:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Edmond Kotowski OK, this makes sense then. Thanks for explanation.'}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-02-18 17:02:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Let me explain this.

User can be granted the access over a database, even the database does not exist.

This is why, I have treated both the cases, absence of access and absence of database as the same.

So, irrespective of existence of database, the message simply means that this revoke command need not be executed.'}, {'account_id': 14009, 'date': '2015-02-18 17:33:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: -Code-Review

Ignoring for the moment whether or not it makes sense to grant access to a DB that does not exist...

We should have parity for granting/revoking access:

If a request to grant access to a non-existent DB succeeds, a request to revoke access from a non-existent DB should also succeed.  If granting access fails, revoking access should fail as well.

As-written, revoking access will fail if the DB does not exist.  And per the comments above, it could easily lead the revoker to believe they don't have access, when in fact they do."}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-02-25 05:56:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Sushil, I'm not sure that statement is correct.

Grant/revoke do work the same for MySQL.  You show 1 grant and 2 revokes.  Your first revoke worked just as the grant did (0 rows affected, no error).  The second revoke failed because the grant on the non-existent DB had already been removed, i.e., it failed on revoke of a non-existent grant, not on revoke of a valid grant on a non-existent DB.

I don't think that our code would distinguish between these 2 cases, since in neither case would there be an actual database associated with the user we are revoking."}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-02-26 10:16:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

So, that is what I want to convey, mysql does not distinguishes between existence of a db, however, what matters for mysql is the existence of a grant, if you have the grant then it could be revoked, irrespective of db existence, and the same is mentioned in the code I have put.'}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2015-02-27 07:03:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-27 08:39:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

commit_message:
Corrects error message for user-access-revoke

Reasons:
- Before revoking the requested database access, current code checks
  whether user has intended access, in the absence of which, service
  prompts the wrong message to user, that database does not exists.
- The error is raised as HTTP 422, unprocessable.

Changes:
- Added new HTTP 422 access forbidden exception to
  inform the lack of access.
- Unit-tests added.
- Integration test updated to verify HTTP-422.

Change-Id: Ifc3010c20324e05a002f674865150c96c331fde3
Closes-Bug: #1302405

commit_message:
Add datastore version and type to backup-list and backup-show

The backup-show and backup-list commands do not show the datastore type
and version, this patch includes it in the list.

Change-Id: I7ca912fa04df94126f509e85e9631d1be1ccaf13
Closes-Bug: #1340367

commit_message:
Readonly functional tests in trove CLI

This patch implements readonly functional tests using trove CLI.
All the unit tests are moved to "unit" directory under "tests" directory.
Functional tests are under "functional" directory under "tests".
Implements: blueprint functional-test-coverage
Depends-On: I60812c49577948bf1bb8a55bbea321e5690f0954
Change-Id: I2d439fa44c686837c9924f154ed5f0d03f6ce911

subject: Adding licensing support for clusters and instances

commit_message:
Adding licensing support for clusters and instances

Introducing licensing support by creating a separate
top level resource for licenses. This would allow
users to BYOL (bring your own license) and to associate
licenses with a particular datastore version.

Change-Id: Ia8b5f920fcc48df0de5dab52166aeab38b67d2a2
Blueprint: trove-license-installation

commit_message:
Make Rsync For Guest Optional

add additional elements in trove-integration to stage the trove code
and trove-guestagent.conf for the guest in the extra-data.d hook, and
subsequently install them in the install.d hook, vs. relying on
upstart/systemd to rsync it.

Change-Id: I960c4cf415ca427df07c48865f1ebc9e20a548a9
Implements: blueprint rsync-optional

[{'created': '2015-04-09 22:26:22.000000000', 'message': "Support CentOS in postgresql config.py path

The PGSQL_CONFIG and PSQL_HBA_CONFIG values need specific
assignment for the 'redhat' family (CentOS, RHEL, Fedora).
The locations of those conf files are defaulted to their
normal location after a call to initdb (/var/lib/pgsql/data).

Change-Id: Ib27f1052291f3ef57e967db7393e70821a7e350e
Closes-Bug: #1442387
"}]
commit_message:
Support CentOS in postgresql config.py path

The PGSQL_CONFIG and PSQL_HBA_CONFIG values need specific
assignment for the 'redhat' family (CentOS, RHEL, Fedora).
The locations of those conf files are defaulted to their
normal location after a call to initdb (/var/lib/pgsql/data).

Change-Id: Ib27f1052291f3ef57e967db7393e70821a7e350e
Closes-Bug: #1442387

commit_message:
Adds guest-exception-handler to resize-volume

- In the absence of the exception handler block in resize-volume-execute
  method, the trove guest was not returning to it original state
  in case of a failure of any guest-methods,
  like if stop_db fails instance gets stuck in resize state.

- Adds the exception handler block to handle any GuestError.
- Removes the status checking block from the same method,
  as there was no purpose of this part because instance is pre-validated
  before sending a resize call for its "ACTIVE" state,
  in simple words, if instance status was not "ACTIVE"
  code will not flow till this point.
- Removes the test which was testing the execute method raising exception
  when called with an instance in ERROR state.

Change-Id: I538513552531f6d302c037b3ae9a315e6bbe2008
Closes-Bug: #1441558

commit_message:
add client management support

Right now the client does not support mgmt api.
So add code to support them. We now support quota,
management, mgmt_cluster, accounts, mgmt_config_params.

Change-Id: I521f1bdc7b83c408e2d38a18296b519b4e24d843
Closes-Bug: #1250258
